{
  "answer": "**No works in the Falsafa corpus provide a vivid, systematic description of judgment after death akin to eschatological accounts in texts like the Bible's Book of Revelation or the Quran's scenes of the scales (e.g., no detailed scales of deeds, resurrection trials, or paradise/hell sentencing).**\n\nHowever, a few works allude to or briefly describe elements of post-mortem judgment:\n\n- **Old English Elegies** (\"Soul and Body II\"): The soul reproaches the body, foretelling their reunion and joint judgment on Doomsday (\"that great day\"), where the Lord will fiercely judge all deeds and wounds, demanding account for sins.[^1] This is the closest to a direct depiction, envisioning divine requital after death.\n\n- **Various Indic Smṛti texts** (e.g., Aṅgirasa Smṛti, Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Paraśara Smṛti): Yama (god of death) is repeatedly portrayed as the post-mortem chastiser/judge of the wicked, weighing sins like false gifts (leading to spikes in Yama's realm) or hidden crimes.[^2][^3] Sinners face Yama's cauldron or specific hells (e.g., Raurava, Kālasūtra) based on deeds, implying karmic judgment, though without procedural detail.\n\n- **Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana**: Yama's southern abode houses sinners' cauldron with \"paths of suffering\"; the protagonist is sent to witness Yama judging them.[^4]\n\nUrdu poetry (e.g., Diwan-E-Ghalib, Bang-E-Dara, Diwan-E-Zauq) and Cynewulf's poems (Andreas, Elene, Juliana) invoke \"qayamat\" (Doomsday) or hell/heaven poetically/metaphorically, but lack descriptive judgment scenes.[^5] French/German political works have no such content.\n\nThe corpus (37 works, mostly Indic law/philosophy, Old English poetry, Urdu ghazals) emphasizes karma, hell-torments, or salvation over explicit afterlife tribunals.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Soul and Body II\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-7f7247).\n\n[^2]: *Aṅgirasa Smṛti*, Ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-93d7c1).\n\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-402a26).\n\n[^4]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, Ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-f907b3).\n\n[^5]: E.g., *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, various ghazals [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/151-nahin-ke-mujh-ko-qayamat-ka-aiteqad-nahin/transliteration/#p-3c0e94); *Andreas*, Ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-861439).",
